{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013ynkLjpoot8dHie8M3f6VX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior from the issue EC-33 about a PR review cycle where a summary comment declared all dimensions PASS even though stored per-dimension findings still contained FAIL verdicts.\n\nThe core problem: manual summary composition without rerunning review agents, and the gate trusted summary text instead of cross-checking stored findings.\n\nLet me reason through each behavior:\n\n**Behavior 1: Storing a PASS review summary is blocked when any stored dimension finding for the same round has a FAIL verdict.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about the interaction between the summary storage layer and the per-dimension findings storage. This is a validation/guard that requires multiple modules (summary writer + findings reader) to interact. \n\nIt's not just one function's logic alone—the validation requires the summary storage to actually read from the per-dimension findings store, so it's a module handoff failure. No OS/network/subprocess needed here, just local storage/DB mocking. If I mock the findings lookup, I'd hide the failure, so I need real data wired together. This is deterministic validation logic checking FAIL verdicts in stored data, no LLM dependency. No single agentic step sequence needed either.\n\n**Behavior 2: Stop-gate verdict computation reads per-dimension stored findings directly and does not rely only on hand-\n\nwritten summary text.**\n\nThe real failure is whether the gate is wired to the correct data source—stored findings versus summary text. If the gate function takes findings as a parameter, this could be a unit test, but the actual issue is the wiring between the gate and its data sources. Mocking the data source would let us pass regardless, so this is integration level testing the module handoff.\n\n**Behavior 3: Manual summary text overrides require an explicit override flag and produce an auditable warning record.**\n\nThis checks one module's behavior—whether the summary writer enforces an override flag and emits a warning when triggered.\n\nThe flag enforcement itself is unit-level, but the \"auditable warning record\" suggests persistence to some store, which pushes this toward integration. If the warning just gets returned or logged in memory, it's unit; if it needs to be stored durably, it's integration. Given the emphasis on auditability, I'm leaning toward integration to verify both the flag enforcement and that the warning record actually persists correctly.\n\nFor Behavior 4, the key failure mode is whether the review loop can be tricked into finalizing without executing a fresh review-agent round on the updated diff. This is integration-level because it requires the loop to actually interact with the review agent—mocking the agent might hide whether the fresh round is truly being executed. The real question is whether we need a genuine LLM call or if mocking the agent and verifying the fresh round was triggered is sufficient. the loop enforces the \"fresh round\" invariant. The behavior is about the LOOP LOGIC (does it require a fresh round?) not about whether the agent produces correct reviews. So we don't need a real LLM - we need to verify the loop's enforcement logic. But we need the agent to be wired into the loop (Integration at minimum). If we mock the agent as \"already ran fresh,\" we wouldn't catch the failure - we need to simulate the case where no fresh round was run. This involves a sequence: Phase 4 fixes happen → loop tries to finalize → should block unless fresh round ran. This is a multi-step workflow concern. The enforcement can be tested at Integration level - stub the review agent with deterministic behavior, verify that calling finalize without a fresh round is blocked. The \"fresh round\" detection is really about loop logic, not LLM output, and the real failure is at the module boundary between loop logic and round tracking.\n\nFor the escalation behavior, this is about loop termination logic - when rounds are exhausted, the flow should produce escalation not PASS. This is deterministic logic about counting rounds and checking finding status, so it could potentially be Unit if it's a pure function, but Integration level seems safer to verify the full flow. All five behaviors are Integration level failures. For behavior 2, even though the gate could theoretically be a pure function, the actual failure was in how it was wired to read summary text instead of findings—that's an integration problem. Behavior 4 involves the fresh round check interacting with the agent's state tracking, which also points to integration rather than unit level.\n\nNow I'm assigning confidence scores to each test level. Behavior 1 is most likely Integration at 0.70 since it crosses module boundaries, with Unit at 0.15 since the validation could theoretically be isolated. Behavior 2 is similar—0.65 Integration, 0.20 Unit—because while the gate function could be tested alone, the real issue was the wiring between modules.\n\nFor Behavior 3, the flag check could be unit-tested at 0.25, but persistence of the audit record pushes it to 0.60 Integration. Behavior 4 is primarily Integration at 0.65, with a small chance of Agentic at 0.10 if fresh rounds involve real LLM calls, though enforcement logic itself doesn't require that. Behavior 5 has loop termination logic that might be a pure function (0.25 Unit), but the integration aspect likely dominates.\n\nNow I need to normalize these so each behavior's weights sum to 1.0.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9452,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9452},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"805014c4-d9c5-4be5-a604-2fa72137f32b","uuid":"46971622-c6d9-4771-aa12-4f32c5f22ce9"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013ynkLjpoot8dHie8M3f6VX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01RAajug5Zq8Yyo4pYp3KbiE","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Storing a PASS review summary is blocked when any stored dimension finding for the same round has a FAIL verdict.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The real failure is at the boundary between two modules — the summary writer and the per-dimension findings store. A unit test on the validation function alone cannot catch a mis-wiring where the validator is never called, or is called against the wrong data. The block must be enforced as the summary write reaches the store, which requires both modules to be wired together under test. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the findings lookup always returns whatever we tell it, hiding any real wiring failure. REAL-INFRA/LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: No subprocess, real network, or LLM needed — deterministic enforcement logic across local modules.","test_description":"Seed a test findings store with one FAIL verdict for dimension D1 and a PASS for D2 in round R1. Attempt to persist a PASS summary for round R1 through the real summary-write path (not mocked). Assert the write is rejected with an appropriate error. Then update the D1 finding to PASS and retry — assert the write now succeeds. Both the findings store and the summary-write module must be the real implementations wired together.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Stop-gate verdict computation reads per-dimension stored findings directly and does not rely only on hand-written summary text.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The root cause in the issue was that the gate was wired to read the wrong data source (summary text instead of stored findings). A unit test that passes pre-parsed findings into the gate function entirely bypasses this wiring failure — it can only be caught when the gate is connected to the real data-fetching layer. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the data source always provides the test-authored value, hiding the real question of which source the gate queries. REAL-INFRA/LLM-DEP: No subprocess or LLM required — the gate logic is deterministic given known stored findings.","test_description":"Write a PASS verdict directly into the summary text field and a FAIL verdict into the per-dimension findings store for the same round. Invoke the stop-gate verdict computation through its real data-access path (no mock on the findings reader). Assert the gate returns FAIL (from stored findings), not PASS (from summary text). This directly reproduces the original incident: if the gate reads only summary text, the test fails.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Manual summary text overrides require an explicit override flag and produce an auditable warning record.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The behavior has two coupled concerns — flag enforcement (block the write without the flag) and audit persistence (the warning record must be durably stored and retrievable). Enforcement alone is Unit-testable, but 'auditable warning record' implies it must be written to a real or in-memory store and then readable by a separate audit reader. That cross-module handoff is the integration boundary. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the warning store would always 'pass' even if the record is never written or written in an incorrect schema. LLM-DEP/REAL-INFRA: None required.","test_description":"Attempt to write a manual summary override without the override flag set; assert it is rejected. Then attempt with the flag set; assert the write succeeds. After the successful write, query the audit record store (real, not mocked) and assert exactly one warning record exists for the override, containing the actor, timestamp, and reason. Verifies both enforcement and durable audit trail in one wired path.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"After Phase 4 fixes, the review loop cannot finalize PASS unless a fresh review-agent round is executed on the updated diff.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is at the boundary between the loop's finalization logic and the round-tracking state: the loop must check whether a review-agent invocation actually occurred against the post-fix diff before allowing PASS. A unit test on finalization logic that accepts a boolean 'fresh_round_ran' parameter entirely bypasses whether the loop correctly sets or reads that flag through real state. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the round tracker always returns whatever we configure, hiding whether finalization actually interrogates the tracker. LLM-DEP: The enforcement predicate (was a round run?) is deterministic — we do not need a real LLM to test the gate; a stub agent that records invocations is sufficient. MULTI-STEP: Only one agentic step is involved; this is not a multi-step workflow.","test_description":"Instantiate the review loop with a stub review agent that records whether it was called and returns deterministic PASS findings. Simulate Phase 4 fix applied (diff updated). Attempt finalization WITHOUT invoking the stub agent post-fix; assert the loop rejects PASS and demands a fresh round. Then invoke the stub agent on the updated diff, then attempt finalization again; assert PASS is allowed. The loop, round tracker, and finalization gate must all be real (not mocked).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.12,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"If review rounds are exhausted with unresolved MUST-FIX findings, the flow emits an escalation outcome instead of PASS.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The escalation logic involves at least two module concerns: the round counter (exhausted?) and the findings classifier (any unresolved MUST-FIX?). The real failure mode is that these two checks are not composed correctly in the flow — e.g., round exhaustion is detected but the wrong outcome branch is taken. A pure-function unit test that receives both inputs as parameters misses any mis-wiring in how the flow assembles those inputs. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking findings always returns the test-authored status, hiding whether the flow actually queries unresolved findings at round exhaustion. LLM-DEP/REAL-INFRA: No real LLM or subprocess needed — deterministic stub agents returning MUST-FIX findings are sufficient. MULTI-STEP: The flow is a single logical gate, not a multi-step agentic pipeline.","test_description":"Configure the review flow with a max-rounds limit of N and a stub review agent that always returns one unresolved MUST-FIX finding. Drive the flow through N complete rounds without resolving the finding. After the final round, assert the flow emits an escalation outcome (not PASS) and that no PASS summary is written to the findings store. The round counter, findings store, and outcome emitter must all be real implementations wired together.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.63,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.04}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9452,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9452},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"805014c4-d9c5-4be5-a604-2fa72137f32b","uuid":"e7402f47-f311-47c4-aa98-e4357b0a396e"}
